        "body": "**Testing strategy for serve command is fragile and incomplete**\n\nMultiple test functions (test_serve_valid_port_zero, test_serve_valid_port_max, test_serve_default_host_and_port) use the same fragile pattern: input='q\\n' and timeout=1 to interrupt the blocking uvicorn.run() call. This approach is unreliable across platforms because uvicorn.run() may not read stdin, and timeout interruption is not guaranteed. Additionally, the assertions are too loose—they verify validation passes but don't actually validate that the server starts correctly. test_serve_default_host_and_port (lines 51-55) checks 'if output contains 127.0.0.1 OR exit_code == 0 OR error appears', which will pass even if startup fails. These tests cannot detect actual server startup failures and do not properly validate the happy path.\n\nRaised by: claude-code\n\nSuggested fix: Refactor into two test categories: (1) CLI validation unit tests that only check argument parsing and port range validation without starting uvicorn (e.g., test argument types, error messages for invalid inputs), (2) separate integration tests that spawn 'factory serve' in a subprocess, verify startup logs indicate successful binding, wait briefly for health check, then terminate cleanly. Replace the input='q\\n', timeout=1 pattern with subprocess-based testing. See suggested_fix for error handling #2 as prerequisite (startup exceptions should produce readable output).",
